      "text": "To ensure the conclusions of our examples follow the premises logically, we annotated all reasoning examples with first-order logic (FOL) formulas."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q18",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Based on our annotations, we propose a new NL-FOL translation task where an NL reasoning example is translated into its FOL counterpart."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q19",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Finally, we benchmark the performance of strong LMs in both fully supervised and few-shot settings to understand their capabilities in logical reasoning (i.e., deriving the truth value of a logical conclusion from NL premises)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q20",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Under the few-shot setting, the most capable publicly available LLM so far achieves only 53.1% on the stories written in a hybrid manner, which is slightly better than random."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q21",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We release a natural language reasoning dataset written by expert annotators, FOLIO, with first-order logical reasoning problems."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q22",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We use formal logic, i.e., FOL to ensure the logical validity of the examples written in NL and propose a new NL-FOL translation task."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q23",
      "page": 2,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We benchmark the performance of LMs by fine-tuning models and prompting LLMs with few-shot examples, on the FOLIO reasoning task."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q24",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We collected FOLIO through a carefully designed manual annotation process to achieve high-quality examples that necessitate complex logical reasoning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q25",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Writing natural language reasoning stories with FOL requires sufficient knowledge in both semantic parsing and first-order logic, as well as strong analytical skills."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q26",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Given the complexities of such annotations, we selected annotators based on a few important criteria to ensures that our dataset is annotated with the highest level of precision and expertise, reflecting the complexity and nuance required for first-order logical reasoning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q27",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Our annotators are either college or graduate students who are native English speakers or possess near-native proficiency in English."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q28",
      "page": 3,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "They possess formal education in first-order logic, having either completed relevant coursework or undertaken self-directed studies in first-order logic or seman-"
    },
    {
      "id": "Q29",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "At the NL quality check stage, only annotators who are experts in natural language processing or computational linguistics are involved. For the FOL quality check, only annotators who are experts in first-order logic are involved."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q30",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We also give the annotators several training sessions on how to write a story, by providing them with detailed annotation guidelines."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q31",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "All stories and FOL annotations in FOLIO are written and reviewed by expert annotators, including CS undergraduate and graduate students, and senior researchers, who met the aforementioned criteria."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q32",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We develop our dataset in six stages: WikiLogic collection, HybLogic collection, NL quality control, FOL quality control, NL-FOL alignment and FOL verification, spending 980 man-hours in total."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q33",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We collected our dataset using two different methods in order to obtain examples that are both logically diverse and complex and have abundant abstract syntax tree (AST) variations."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q34",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "WikiLogic: annotation from scratch using Wikipedia articles as seeds. At this annotation stage, the annotators are asked to select random Wikipedia pages by repeatedly using the Wikipedia Special Random link. The Wikipedia articles are used to develop ideas for topics to write new stories."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q35",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We ask the annotators to create new stories from scratch without using templates based on real-world knowledge, which should be plausible in general."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q36",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Each of the stories is composed of several premises and conclusions with truth values of True, False, or Unknown (see Table 2 for an example)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q37",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We also ask the annotators to write parallel FOL sentences for both the premises and conclusions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q38",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "This results in a wide range of topics, abundant AST variations, and a wide vocabulary for FOLIO."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q39",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "HybLogic: hybrid annotation The task of generating logically sound stories from scratch for a set of facts is very time-consuming for human writers, where the main challenge is to create complex and varied logical patterns to arrive at a conclusion."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q40",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "To address the problems of solely using manual annotation, we also consider a hybrid approach to facilitate the process. Our hybrid method is based on a common form of logical stories: syllogisms."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q41",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "A syllogism consists of two premises and a single conclusion, and the conclusion states some facts about the entities and categories in the premises."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q42",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "In this approach, we first generate logically valid stories, which are templates containing abstract categories and entities, by combining multiple syllogisms into a single story template: the conclusion of one syllogism is used as a premise for the next syllogism."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q43",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "There are 256 logically distinct types of syllogisms and 24 of them are valid (Lehman, 1973). We use various combinations of 24 valid syllogisms. We also add in conjunction, disjunction, and implication."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q44",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We then ask human annotators to assign nouns, phrases, or clauses to the abstract entities or categories that reflect real-life scenarios to each template and write logically-valid stories in natural language."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q45",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "The usage of the template is to ensure that we have a set of varied and complex logical stories with multiple conclusions. There are many ways of expressing the same logic template in natural language, and so the generated templates augment, rather than limit, the creativity of humans."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q46",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "To ensure the highest quality of the dataset, we dedicated considerable attention to the following key aspects of the natural language sentences during the quality control process."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q47",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Our dataset prioritizes realism and factual accuracy, steering clear of biases and stereotypes linked to identity markers like race, ethnicity, gender, sexuality, nationality, class, and religion."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q48",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Toward these objectives, we manually screened all stories and found that 39.2% of the stories suffer from at least one of these issues. We implemented a detailed protocol to rewrite these stories."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q49",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Apart from grammar, we make sure the sentences in our dataset are highly natural. All the sentences are first checked with a grammar checking tool, Grammarly."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q50",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Our annotators who have graduated from or are senior students studying English Literature conducted a thorough round of review for grammatical correctness and language naturalness."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q51",
      "page": 4,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We also eliminate natural language ambiguity when it is possible."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q52",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We adopt the FOL definitions and syntax most widely used in the AI community (Russell and Norvig, 2010)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q53",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "In preliminary investigations, we found that the human-written FOL formulas suffer from FOL consistency issues, which necessitates an additional round of quality control for FOL formulas."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q54",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "One NL sentence can be translated into FOL through multiple non-equivalent ways. For example, sometimes additional information inferred from a sentence can be represented in FOL, leading to multiple representations. We therefore design an annotation protocol for FOL translation in order to ensure that our FOL translations are as consistent as possible across all examples in our dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q55",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Apart from checking whether NL and FOL express equivalent meanings, we also add necessary commonsense knowledge in both the NL and FOL premises. Sometimes humans do not write certain commonsense knowledge in the premises that is required in the FOL reasoning process, which is based solely on the premises given. We add such knowledge as additional premises at this stage."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q56",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In particular, intrinsic properties of some predicates are required in the FOL reasoning process. For example, \"LocatedIn(x,y)\" should be transitive and \"BeFamily(x,y)\" should be symmetric."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q57",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Recognizing that the FOL formula annotations can be error-prone, we verify the syntactic validity and label consistency of FOL formula annotations with an FOL inference engine."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q58",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Table 3 shows that examples based on Wikipedia make up the largest portion of FOLIO, with 304 stories, 1,353 NL and FOL premise pairs, and 753 NL and FOL conclusion pairs. Hybrid annotations consist of 183 stories with 1,054 NL and FOL premise pairs, and 682 NL and FOL conclusion pairs in total."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q59",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We use the Dale-Chall Readability Formula (Dale and Chall, 1948, 1995) to show the text complexity of FOLIO following (Singh et al., 2023; Arps et al., 2022; Wei et al., 2021)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q60",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "As shown in Figure 1, the mode of reasoning depths is four in FOLIO. 28.7% of the examples need five or more depths of reasoning to infer the conclusions, while the previous datasets needed at most five reasoning depths as shown in Table 1."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q61",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Table 1 shows that FOLIO also has a much larger number of distinct ASTs than the previous datasets, indicating that FOLIO is much more logically diverse."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q62",
      "page": 5,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Table 3 shows that our dataset has a vocabulary of 4,351 words, and the examples based on Wikipedia account for 74% of the total vocabulary even though the WikiLogic stories take up only 63% of the total number of stories."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q63",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We define two new tasks based on FOLIO, natural language reasoning with first-order logic and NL-FOL translation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q64",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Each natural language (NL) story S in FOLIO consists of n premises: P = {p1, p2, ..., pn} and m conclusions: H = {h1, h2, ..., hm}."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q65",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "All NL stories are annotated with parallel FOL stories SF, which are sets of FOL formulas consisting of n premises PF = {pf1, pf2, ..., pfn} and m conclusions HF = {hf1, hf2, ..., hfm}."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q66",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "Given P and H, the goal is to determine the truth values of the conclusions: \"True\", \"False\" or \"Unknown\", based on FOL reasoning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q67",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We propose a new natural language to first-order logic translation (NL-FOL translation) task alongside our reasoning dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q68",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In particular, each of the NL sentence pi or hi and the parallel FOL formula pfi or hfi should be logically and semantically equivalent."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q69",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "Moreover, the truth values for the conclusions should be the same based on the NL story S and the parallel FOL story FS."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q70",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In our dataset, the premises and conclusions are set up in such a way to ensure that the inference engine always returns an answer given enough resources such as time and memory."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q71",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Unlike previous work (Singh et al., 2020) which translates problems with a single premise and a single hypothesis, our task is on translating examples of various lengths with a focus on stories with multiple premises."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q72",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "Thus, it also requires the models to consider discourse-level consistencies as opposed to translation at the sentence level."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q73",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Two metrics are adopted to evaluate NL-FOL translation to capture different aspects of the generation results: 1). Syntactic validity (SynV)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q74",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The Syntactic Validity score measures whether the FOL formulas are syntactically valid. The score will be 1 if all FOL formulas of an example can pass the syntactic check and 0 otherwise 2)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q75",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Inference Engine execution accuracy (ExcAcc). The group of translated FOL for premises and conclusions in one story is fed into our inference engine to output the truth value for each conclusion."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q76",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We define the accuracy of the output labels as the execution accuracy."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q77",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We leave for future work the design of a more reliable metric of NL-FOL translation."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q78",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We split FOLIO by 70%/15%/15% split for the train/validation/test sets with 1,001/203/226 examples respectively."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q79",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We split by story so that models are evaluated on unseen stories."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q80",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We use accuracy for evaluating logical reasoning performance."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q81",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "For NL-FOL translation, we use the metrics in Section 4.2."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q82",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We test the logical reasoning capabilities of LMs using fully supervised fine-tuning and few-shot prompting."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q83",
      "page": 6,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We also test NL-FOL translation with few-shot prompting."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q84",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "As fine-tuning baselines, we experiment with BERT (Devlin et al., 2019), and RoBERTa (Liu et al., 2020)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q85",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "We fine-tune the base and large versions of both BERT and RoBERTa, with an additional two-layer classification layer to predict the truth values."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q86",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For the second task, i.e., NL-FOL translation, we only report few-shot prompting methods."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q87",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We conduct zero-shot and few-shot prompting experiments on larger LMs with few-shot capabilities."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q88",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "For open-source models, we test LLaMA-13B and LLaMA-70B (Touvron et al., 2023), GPT-NeoX-20B (Black et al., 2022); for proprietary models we test GPT-3 (Brown et al., 2020), GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4 (OpenAI et al., 2023) using prompts with 8 examples."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q89",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We experiment with incorporating recent prompting strategies into GPT-4 as they have shown improvements in the general reasoning performance of LLMs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q90",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "The prompting strategies include chain-of-thought (CoT) prompting (Wei et al., 2022b), chain-of-thought prompting with self-consistency (Wang et al., 2023) and tree-of-thought prompting (Yao et al., 2023)."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q91",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We also test recent methods specifically designed for logical reasoning: Logic-LM (2023), LINC (Olausson et al., 2023) and DetermLR(Sun et al., 2023), using GPT-4 as the base model."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q92",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "For the second task (NL-FOL translation), we use the same examples as in the Few-Shot NL experiments except that all the conclusions are included in each example."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q93",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "We run experiments on five randomly sampled sets of examples from the training set and report the average accuracy."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q94",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "output_ontology",
      "text": "The majority baseline of our dataset is 38.5% since in our test set, there are 87, 78 and 61 examples with labels of true, false and unknown respectively."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q95",
      "page": 7,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In experimenting with different prompts, we found 8 shot examples to perform slightly better. It is also the maximum number of examples that fits in the text-davinci-002 context."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q96",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Table 5 shows the results of NL-FOL translation. The syntactic validity scores are around 93% with both GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4. This indicates that language models with sufficient scales are good at picking up the patterns for FOL formulas and generating syntactically valid FOL formulas."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q97",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "However, GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4 are not yet good at translating an NL story to a logically or semantically similar FOL counterpart, as indicated by the low inference engine execution accuracy score."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q98",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Below we provide analysis of our results and key findings, providing additional insights into our dataset FOLIO and the current capabilities of LLMs in logical reasoning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q99",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "With few-shot prompting, GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 both perform much better on examples with a 0 ∼ 3 reasoning depth, indicating that examples with a 4 ∼ 7 reasoning depth pose a challenge to the SoTA LMs."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q100",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "This indicates that fine-tuning on longer and more difficult reasoning chains in the training set can improve model performance on equally-long test example chains."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q101",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "FOLIO's unique complexity reveals that current LMs are limited in their ability to extrapolate to longer and more complex reasoning chains, and suggests an avenue for further study."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q102",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "As shown in Table 6, in logical reasoning, GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 achieve substantially lower results on HybLogic than on WikiLogic and the result is slightly higher than chance."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q103",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "We hypothesize that this is because HybLogic has high logical complexity that the SoTA LLMs like GPT-4 cannot solve yet while WikiLogic examples require shorter reasoning chains which the model is already capable of solving."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q104",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Moreover, since the examples in WikiLogic are created from scratch by humans, it is possible that LLMs have seen similar texts with similar logical patterns in the training data."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q105",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "However, fine-tuning RoBERTa-large achieves higher performance on HybLogic than on WikiLogic. This is likely because HybLogic is created from templates and some of the logical patterns can be learned during fine-tuning."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q106",
      "page": 8,
      "dimension": "input_form",
      "text": "In NL-FOL translation, performs 10 points better on HybLogic than WikiLogic. This could be because WikiLogic has more distinct and diverse sentence-level logical and language patterns and FOL annotations. WikiLogic has 53 ASTs while HybLogic has 33."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q107",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We collected truth value annotations of logical reasoning for FOLIO test set from expert and non-expert annotators."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q108",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Our expert annotators are computer science college students familiar with FOL."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q109",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Non-expert annotators are community college or high school students who have not taken the SAT."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q110",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Both expert and non-expert annotators are native English speakers."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q111",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Expert annotations achieve an accuracy of 95.98% while non-expert annotations achieves 61.82%, with a gap of 34.16%."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q112",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_ontology",
      "text": "This shows that sufficient domain knowledge of FOL is necessary for good performance on FOLIO."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q113",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "The expert and GPT-4 gap is 31.82%, suggesting significant room for model improvement."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q114",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "We focus on collecting a very high-quality dataset in evaluating logical reasoning rather than merely a large dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q115",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_content",
      "text": "Optimizing for quality required us to adopt a rigorous annotation process with domain experts selected based on a few important criteria as mentioned in Appendix A: Annotator Selection."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q116",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "Significantly scaling up this process would have required resources beyond our current means and we are unable further expand our dataset for investigating how the size of training data affects the performance of fine-tuning experiments."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q117",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "input_content",
      "text": "We encourage the community to apply our annotation protocol to expand this realistic and complex FOL reasoning story set."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q118",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "Approximately 65% of the time, the model struggles to construct accurate reasoning chains for complex problems with intricate steps, leading to faulty reasoning paths and indicating a limited ability to solve problems with long reasoning chains."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q119",
      "page": 9,
      "dimension": "output_form",
      "text": "In 25% of cases, erroneous derivations occur within certain reasoning steps, highlighting potential inaccuracies and flaws in logical deductions."
    },
    {
      "id": "Q120",
